<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=101022876717207></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f101022876717207><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=5&mid=101022876717207>Strategy On Using a Shadow Knight</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=5&mid=101022876717207#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=133606><span id= >Kallirye</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>8 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sat, Jan 5th 6:06 AM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[4.25]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>My strategy is aimed at lower level Shadow Knights about level 13.  Though many of the elements can be implemented at higher levels.<br><br>First off I would like to say that from my experience, a properly used SK is one of the more powerful classes in the game.  Just today, I dueled a level 16 Rogue ( I am 13) and I won.  Strategy in Dueling is especially critical, because your fighting against a 'thinking' opponent, that does not have programmed responses you can anticipate.  Now, half of the strategy of a duel is determined before the duel is even fought.  If your going to fight a duel with another player, make sure you go off by yourselves in at least a semi secluded area.  The key is, you don't want outside interference, especially in the form of group members healing.  The second thing you should be aware of and anticipate, is the fact that the other person may have buffs, increasing his power above what he cons.  If possible, acquire some of your own buffs and if able, find a weapon or item that procs debuff in combat, like the Stalagterror Spear, which I use.  Hopefully, it will proc during the duel and neutralize any buffs he may have, something he won't anticipate.<br><br>  Now here's a trick that is very effective, if you have your pet summoned, great, if not, wait until HE initiates the duel, waiting for you to type in /d to accept.  Then quickly cast Leering Corpse and as soon as the pet is summoned, accept the duel.  He has no idea what your casting, and probably thinks it's some sort of buff, he'll be surprised when your pet skeleton walks out and then before he can react, you and the pet start beating on him.  He is now forced to do one of two things:  Either kill the pet first (because it's weakest) or go straight for you and allow the pet to beat on him for the remainder of the duel.  Either way, it works out for your benefit.  This is a completely honorable tactic, you are able and allowed to summon a pet as part of your repertoire, before or during the fight (if you can), the tactic, however, is to catch him by surprise, because he doesn't expect it.<br><br>  Now, if he starts beating on the pet, this is your chance to not only get in some free hits, but to cast your DoT Disease Cloud, your Debuff/Buff Syphon Strength, and then start hitting him continuously with Life Tap.  Now, you may not think these spells do very much damage, but they quickly add up ove time, and I've been through many duels, where the last person standing had only a few hit points left.  The loss of strength to Him is crucial in two ways, first it will slightly decrease his maximum damage (not very noticeable, but it adds up, like everything else), but secondly, if he's fool enough to being on the verge of encumbered, it will encumber him, causing his agility to drop and making him easier to hit, consider it a double debuff!  Now each one of these in itself, is not very significant, but combined, they will have major effect in the duel, and truly all your fights as a Shadow Knight.<br><br>  Your pet will most likely die after your first few spells (your pets just aren't very strong, like your spells, he is supplemental to YOUR fighting strength, to be effective).  Now the real action begins, as he turns his fury onto you.  You may think about hitting him with your Harm Touch right away, but DON'T. Save it, trust me.  I prefer to use a shield when I fight, mainly because it gives me an extra attack in the form of a bash, which is good for disruptiing spellcasters.  If you use a shield, you may be tempted to hit the BASH key as soon as it lights up, don't, what you want to do is time it so it goes off approx in between your primary weapons attacks.  Here's why, if you've ever played a caster you know, that you want to time your spells to go off, just after the enemy has hit you, so you have the maximum amount of time to get the spell off before he swings again.  Your opponent (if he can cast) will do the same thing.  He will attempt to time his casting, to just after you swing with your primary, leaving you open to his spells.  This is when you want to use your bash, to fill this gap in your defence and try to disrupt any spells he trys to cast at you.  If used correctly, between Life Tap, Bash, and your primary attack, the enemy will have a barrage of attacks coming at him &quot;constantly&quot; instead of one massive attack, then a long pause.<br><br><br>Of course, if he's smart, your opponent will try to do the same thing to you to disrupt YOUR spell casting, this is where you have to remember to stay on your feet!  Your not fighting a mob,  your fighting a human, mobs will automatically turn to face you, humans can get confused and turn the wrong way or over step!  Whatever you do, don't stand still, move constantly in a NON RYTHMIC pattern, don't let the enemy anticipate you, be spontaneous and sporadic, go one way, then suddenly go the other way, and even walk right over him and turn around and start bashing!  Remember, if your enemy cant see you, he cant hit you.<br><br>  On a more expert note, if you can learn to time when YOUR weapon will swing, step back out of the way of HIS attack, then step IN for YOUR attack, then step back out again.  This forces him to keep moving to stay within range and will prevent him from having many opportunites to cast a spell, since you can't cast a spell while moving.<br><br>  Now when YOU want to cast a spell, I've found the best tactic is to wait until just after YOU'VE swung, then run through him to the other side, turn and start casting,  Now you will be out of range with your weapon, but more than likely he will rush up to YOU so HE can be in range with HIS weapon, so by the time he gets in range, your spell has or is about to go off and your ready for your next swing, so you haven't missed a single opportunity to attack.  Of course all this takes practice, so ask another person to duel with you and agree before hand to fight until only 1 bubble.  Make sure to fight near a zone though, in case he tries to trick you.<br><br>  For the finale, remeber that Harm Touch I told you to save?  Here's why, most characters that have the ability to heal themselves (or from my experience, other group members sticking there noses in during the fight) will not attempt to heal, at least a major heal, until there life is about 1/3 or less, until then, most players like to see if they can handle you with out resorting to it, or are busy casting attack spells and moving around to concentrate on healing.  Once a player realizes he is starting to lose or at least, get seriously hurt, he will try to pull back and heal himself like crazy (if he has the ability) he may even have a trick up his sleeve like a item that procs heal, or in the case of Paladins 1 Lay on Hands.  Up until this time, throughout the fight, he has realized how much damage you can do over a period of time and will best estimate when he should start healing ( again at about 1/3 life) and think he has more than enough time.  NOW is when you hit him with your Harm Touch and if timed correctly will kill him INSTANTLY before he has a chance to react or at the very least drain his life so low, that a few more blows he is dead.  No chance to run, No chance for a group member to intervene, No chance for any trick healing, BAM, its over before he knows it.<br><br>  I can personally attest to the effectiveness of these tactics and I use them successfully over and over against opponents who often are higher level than me.  One basic overall strategy to keep in mind is this:  A Shadow Knight has many different abilities (or weapons) like his spells, pets, and harm touch, none of these however is strong enough to rely soley on and as a straight fighter, a warrior will outperform you, you must realize one important thing, all these abilities are supplemental to ONE thing, YOUR fighting ability.  If your fighting ability sucks, none of those abilities will save you ( I'm speaking over all, not a specific battle), but if your fighting abilities are good or great, they will SUPPLEMENT your ability giving you an extra edge and raising you from a good fighter to a great fighter or great to outstanding.  I hope this strategy will help new Shadow Knights in realizing thier full potential.  If you have any questions or comments, post or email me and your welcome to send a tell in the game, I'm on Brell Serelis.<br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Sat Jan  5 06:17:02 2002</em><br>&nbsp;<br>Daughter of Hate, Shadow Knight of TheDead, Dedicated of Innoruuk, Consort of Emperor Crush.</td></tr>
